To set a maximum episode length when training with Rllib, you can use the "evaluation_duration" and "evaluation_duration_unit" settings. Set "evaluation_duration" to the desired maximum length and "evaluation_duration_unit" to either "episodes" or "timesteps" depending on your preference. For example, if you want to set a maximum of 10 episodes, you can use:

{
    "evaluation_duration": 10,
    "evaluation_duration_unit": "episodes"
}

To specify the Python version in the runtime environment, you can use the "python_version" parameter in the "pip" field. For example:

RuntimeEnv(
    pip={"packages": ["tensorflow", "requests"], "pip_check": False, "pip_version": "==22.0.2;python_version=='3.8.11'"}
)

To create an actor instance with parameters, you can use the `.remote()` method on the actor class and pass the desired arguments to the constructor. For example:

```python
@ray.remote
class Greeter:
    def __init__(self, value):
        self.value = value

    def say_hello(self):
        return self.value

# Create an actor instance with a parameter.
greeter = Greeter.remote("Hello, World!")
```

This will create a new actor instance with the specified parameter.
